\begin_layout Standard
We will start by reviewing IVPMs in the classical setting
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JamisonLodwick2004"

\end_inset

 and then propose our quantum framework.
 In the classical setting, there are several proposals for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imprecise probabilities.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Although these proposals differ in some details, they all share the fact
 that the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)$
\end_inset

 of an event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is generalized from a single real number to an interval of certainty 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 intuitively corresponds to the strength of evidence for the event and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the strength of evidence against the event.
 The collection of intervals used in the definition of a probability measure
 must satisfy certain properties which we explain next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First for each interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

 we have the natural constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\ell\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

 that guarantees that every element of the interval can be interpreted as
 a conventional probability.
 We also include 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs=[0,0]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess=[1,1]$
\end_inset

 as limiting intervals to refer to the probability of impossible events
 (e.g., the null event) and certain events (e.g., the event covering the entire
 space).
 For each interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

, we also need the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[1-r,1-\ell]$
\end_inset

 so that if one interval refers to the probability of an event, the other
 refers to the probability of the complement event.
 For example, if we discover as a result of an experiment that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)=[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 for some event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, we may conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})=[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

 for the complement event 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition to these simple conditions, there are some subtle conditions
 on how intervals are combined, which we discuss next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 be to disjoint events with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1})=[\ell_{1},r_{1}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{2})=[\ell_{2},r_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 A first attempt at calculating the probability of the combined event that
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 occurs might be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}+E_{2})=[\ell_{1}+\ell_{2},r_{1}+r_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 In some cases, this is indeed a sensible definition.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1})=[0.1,0.2]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{2})=[0.3,0.4]$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}+E_{2})=[0.4,0.6]$
\end_inset

.
 But consider an event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)=[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})=[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

.
 The two events are disjoint; the previous na√Ø ve way of combining the intervals
 would give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E+\overline{(}E))=[0.9,1.1]$
\end_inset

 which is not a valid probability interval.
 Moreover the event 
\begin_inset Formula $E+\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 is the identity event covering the entire space; its probability interval
 should be 
\begin_inset Formula $[1,1]$
\end_inset

 which is sharper than 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.9,1.1]$
\end_inset

.
 The problem is that the two intervals are correlated: there is more information
 in the combined event than in each event separately.
 In our example, even though the true probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)$
\end_inset

 can be in anywhere in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 and the true probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})$
\end_inset

 can be in anywhere in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

, the values are not independent.
 Any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)\leq0.25$
\end_inset

 will force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})\geq0.75$
\end_inset

.
 To account for such subtleties, the axioms of interval-valued probability
 do not use a strict equality for the combination of disjoint events.
 The correct constraint regarding the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}+E_{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}+E_{2})\subseteq[\ell_{1}+\ell_{2},r_{1}+r_{2}]$
\end_inset

 which, in combination with the requirement for the identity event would
 force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E+\overline{E})$
\end_inset

 to always be 
\begin_inset Formula $[1,1]$
\end_inset

 irrespective of the particular assignments of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})$
\end_inset

.
 When combining non-disjoint events, there is a further subtlety whose resolutio
n will give the most general and final condition as follows.
 For general, non-necessarily disjoint events 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu(E_{1}+E_{2})+\mu(E_{1}E_{2})\subseteq\mu(E_{1})+\mu(E_{2})\label{eq:classicalconvex}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is a generalization of the classical inclusion-exclusion principle
 that uses 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $=$
\end_inset

 for the same reason as before.
 The new condition reduces to the previously motivated condition when the
 events are disjoint, i.e., when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}E_{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have the necessary ingredients to define QIVPMs as a generalization
